From the power law to extreme value mixture distribution

2024-06-30

Outline

  • Networks \(\times\) extreme value theory

 

  • Slides: https://bit.ly/sunbelt2024

Why the power law?

  • Empirically observed
  • Scale-free networks potentially generated from “nice” models
    • Preferential attachment
    • Generalised random graphs

Does it really follow the power law?

  • Survival plots to show

Some ways of testing / modelling degree distribution

  • Broido and Clauset (2019)
  • Voitalov et al. (2019)
  • Artico et al. (2020)
  • Valero, Pérez-Casany, and Duarte-López (2022)

Some related articles

  • on discrete extremes
  • mostly for power-law-related data

Issues

  • Above or below a threshold?
  • Comparing fits with different thresholds
  • Subjective choices \(\rightarrow\) different conclusions
  • Large degrees influencing the fit too much

Mixture model

  • “Medium” degrees by a generalisation of discrete power law
    • Zipf-Mandelbrot \(+\) Zipf-polylog (Valero, Pérez-Casany, and Duarte-López 2022)
    • Toggle between power law (straight line) or not (curved)
  • Large degrees by integer generalised Pareto (IGP) distribution
    • No direct relationship with above distributions
  • A straight line but curving off
  • SCHEMATIC

Tail heaviness

  • \(1/(\alpha-1)\) implied by the power law
  • \(\xi\) actual from IGP

Relationships

For CRAN data

  • Fit suggests mixture model is essential (\(u\) is not hitting either boundary)
  • Better than alternatives (marginal likelihood)

For simulated data

  • Even simulated data prefers mixture model! (confirm marginal likelihood)
  • Using the theoretical line questionable
  • Finite sample behaviour

Comparison

  • Plot \(\xi\) against \(1/(\alpha-1)\) to show difference
  • Reassuring

Fit over time

  • Constantly lighter than implied by the body
  • At the same time, relatively stable
